ies (NHL)|Colorado Rockies]] in 1976, but subsequently moved again and were renamed the [[New Jersey Devils]] in 1982.|group=note}}\n| 5\n| {{sort|1|[[Colorado Rapids|Rapids]]}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[Phoenix metropolitan area|Phoenix]]\n| United States\n| 13\n| 4,661,537\n| 4\n| {{sort|1|[[Arizona Cardinals|Cardinals]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Arizona Diamondbacks|Diamondbacks]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Phoenix Suns|Suns]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Arizona Coyotes|Coyotes]]}}\n| 4\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[Metro Detroit|Detroit]]\n| United States\n| 14\n| 4,297,617\n| 4\n| {{sort|1|[[Detroit Lions|Lions]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Detroit Tigers|Tigers]]}}{{refn|The [[Detroit Wolverines]] played in the [[National League]] from 1881 until the team disbanded in 1888.|group=note}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Detroit Pistons|Pistons]]}}{{refn|The [[Detroit Falcons (basketball)|Detroit Falcons]] played in the [[1946-47 BAA season|inaugural season]] of what would become the NBA, but disbanded following that season.|group=note}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Detroit Red Wings|Red Wings]]}}\n| 4\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014}}\n|-\n| [[Greater Toronto Area|Toronto]]\n| Canada\n| 10\n| 5,928,040\n| 3\n| align=center|{{sort|0|\u2014 {{refn|While Toronto has not had an NFL franchise, the [[Buffalo Bills]] did host one of the team's regular season games each year and a number of pre-season games at the [[Rogers Centre]] from 2008 to 2013 as part of the [[Bills Toronto Series]].|group=note}}}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Toronto Blue Jays|Blue Jays]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Toronto Raptors|Raptors]]}}{{refn|The [[Toronto Huskies]] played in the [[1946-47 BAA season|inaugural season]] of what would become the NBA, before dissolving.|group=note}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Toronto Maple Leafs|Maple Leafs]]}}\n| 5\n| {{sort|1|[[Toronto FC]]}}\n| {{sort|1|[[Toronto Argonauts|Argonauts]]}}\n|-\n| [[Greater Houston|Houston]]\n| United States\n| 5\n| 6,772,470\n| 3\n| {{sort|1|[[H